</ul>
<h3><b>13.Tickeron — AI Trading Platform for Signals and Market Analysis</b></h3>
<p><b></b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Tickeron is an AI trading platform built mainly for traders who want market signals, pattern analysis, and AI-powered trade ideas across stocks, ETFs, and some crypto tools. On its official site, Tickeron presents its product lineup around AI Trading Agents, AI Trend Prediction, AI Stock Screener, Real-Time Patterns, and daily buy/sell signals, making it more of an AI trading research and signal platform than a fully hands-free managed bot service.</span></p>
<p><b>Key Features:</b></p>
<ul>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">AI Trading Agents and AI trading bots for stocks, ETFs, and some crypto-focused tools.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">AI Trend Prediction Engine with entry and exit guidance plus confidence levels.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">AI Stock Screener and Real-Time Pattern tools for market scanning.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Daily buy/sell signals and a 14-day free trial highlighted on official pages.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pricing varies by tool and promotion, with free trial access available on official pages. </span></li>
</ul>
<h3><b>14.Capitalise.ai — No-Code Automated Trading Platform</b></h3>
<p><b></b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Capitalise.ai is a no-code trading automation platform built for users who want to create and run trading strategies in plain English. On its official site, it says traders can create, test, simulate, and automate trading scenarios without coding, while the system monitors markets 24/7 and executes trades automatically when conditions are met. That makes it a strong option for beginners who want rule-based automation without learning programming.</span></p>
<p><b>Key Features:</b></p>
<ul>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">No-code trading automation using everyday English.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Backtesting, simulation, and live automated execution.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">24/7 market monitoring and smart notifications.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Supports advanced conditions based on technical indicators, time frames, macro events, and TradingView alerts.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pricing: the support page says users can sign up for free with no monthly charges, though that may change in the future. </span></li>
</ul>
<h3><b>15.StockHero — Automated Stock Trading Bot for Beginners</b></h3>
<p><b><br />
</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> StockHero is an automated trading platform built mainly for stock traders who want to create and run bots without coding. On its official site, StockHero says users can deploy preset bots from its Marketplace, automate trades with supported brokerages, and manage bots through a web app and mobile app. It positions itself as a beginner-friendly platform with simple setup, paper trading, and cloud-based automation, making it more suitable for stock bot users than for crypto-only traders.</span></p>
<p><b>Key Features:</b></p>
<ul>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">No coding required.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Supports preset bots and bot deployment through its Marketplace.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Includes paper trading and automated bot testing.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Supports TradingView signal automation and multiple strategy types such as DCA, grid, long/short, and high-frequency styles.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pricing: free plan available, with paid tiers for more advanced features.</span></li>
</ul>
<h2><b>Do You Need to Pay Taxes on AI Trading Bots?</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Using an AI trading bot does not usually change whether your crypto activity is taxable. In the United States, the IRS says digital assets are treated as property, which means selling, exchanging, or otherwise disposing of crypto can trigger tax consequences. The UK’s HMRC also says you may need to pay Capital Gains Tax when you sell, exchange, or give away cryptoassets, while Australia’s ATO explains that crypto tax treatment depends on how you acquire, hold, and dispose of the asset. In other words, automated trading is still trading for tax purposes.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If your AI bot places trades frequently, recordkeeping becomes even more important. You should normally track buys, sells, swaps, fees, and the value of assets at the time of each transaction. In some situations, the tax treatment may be different from standard capital gains treatment. HMRC notes that if activity is considered trading, Income Tax can apply instead of Capital Gains Tax, though it says this would be exceptional for individuals. The IRS also says digital assets received for services are generally ordinary income. Because rules vary by country and can change over time, it is smart to keep detailed records and check local tax guidance or speak with a tax professional before filing. </span></p>
<h2><b>FAQ</b></h2>
<h3><b>Are there really AI trading apps?</b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Yes. AI trading apps and AI-assisted trading platforms do exist, although they vary a lot in what they actually do. Some focus on market analysis and trading assistance, such as ChainGPT’s AI Trading Assistant, while others focus on automated bot execution, such as Cryptohopper and Pionex. In practice, “AI trading app” can mean anything from an AI market scanner to a fully automated trading bot, so it is important to check the platform’s actual features instead of relying on the label alone.</span></p>
<h3><b>Is AI trading legal?</b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In general, using AI tools or bots for trading is not automatically illegal, but legality depends on where you live, what asset you are trading, and whether the platform is operating properly under local rules. Investors should also be careful because regulators have warned that scammers often misuse AI language to promote fake or deceptive investment products. That means the key issue is not just “AI trading,” but whether the product, promotion, and provider are legitimate in your jurisdiction.</span></p>
<h3><b>Does AI trading really work?</b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">AI trading can be useful for tasks such as scanning markets, detecting patterns, generating alerts, backtesting strategies, and automating execution. That said, “working” does not mean guaranteed profits. Even official product pages usually describe tools for analysis, automation, and strategy support, while regulators warn investors not to confuse advanced technology claims with proven performance. AI may improve speed and efficiency, but results still depend on market conditions, strategy quality, fees, and risk control.</span></p>
<h3><b>Can I make money with AI trading?</b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">You can make money with AI trading, but you can also lose money. No legitimate platform can promise high returns with little or no risk, and the SEC specifically warns investors to be skeptical of those kinds of claims. AI tools may help traders automate decisions and react faster, but profitability is never guaranteed, especially in volatile markets like crypto.</span></p>
<h3><b>Can we trust AI trading?</b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">AI trading should be approached with caution, not blind trust. A platform may be useful, but investors should still verify who operates it, understand how the strategy works, review fees, and watch for classic red flags such as guaranteed profits, pressure to act fast, fake testimonials, or vague claims about “secret AI systems.” The safest approach is to treat AI as a tool, not a promise, and to rely on due diligence and risk management before committing funds. </span></p>
